                    analysis to establish the long run relationship between the relevant time series data. The results
                    revealed that short term interest rate on deposits, population growth rate and national output
                    (real gross domestic rate) have direct and significant effects on demand for money in Nigeria,
                    whereas interest rate (on lending) have indirect and significant effects on demand for money.
                    The Autoregressive Distributed Lag bounds test revealed the existence of co-integration at 5%
                    significance level. The result showed that although there was a break in 1989, demand for
                    money still became stable even after the break as the dummy and interactive term used in
                    one-step Chowed test showed significance at 5% significance level. There is need to formulate
                    policies that will reduce lending interest rate which include but not limited to influencing of the
                    monetary policy rate statutorily determined by the Central Bank of Nigeria.</article>
