            <details>
                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> This study assessed the contributory role of deposit money
                    banks to agricultural sector growth
                    in Nigeria. Secondary data were sourced from the Central Bank of Nigeria statistical bulletin
                    from 1986 to 2018. Augmented Dickey Fuller (ADF), Bound Test and Autoregressive Distributed
                    Lag (ARDL) were used to analyze the sourced data. Unit root test showed that lending rate
                    and government allocation to agriculture were stationary at level while agricultural sector
                    output and bank credit to agricultural sector were stationary at first difference. It was revealed
                    in the Bounds test result that there was a long-run relationship among the variables specified
                    in the model. Autoregressive distributed lag results indicated that bank credit to agricultural
                    sector had positive and significant effect on agricultural sector output in the long-run. In the
                    same vein, government allocation to agricultural sector equally had positive but insignificant
                    effect on the agricultural sector output. It was concluded that deposit money banks had been
                    serving as an important instrument for achieving increased and sustainable agricultural sector
                    growth in Nigeria. The recommendations were that the deposit money banks should be
                    encouraged, through provision of enabling operating environment by the authorities, to lend
                    more to the sector at the right time with right price; and that increased as well as monitored
                    funds should be allocated to the sector by the government.</article>
            </details>
