                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> The interests of every educational institution is centered on
                    how to produce a world class and
                    well equipped graduates so as to improve the standard of living in the society. Institutions of
                    higher learning can only achieve their goals and objectives when the right input (employees)
                    perform their jobs as expected and optimally. This study aimed at examining the moderating
                    effect of emotional intelligence in the relationship between leadership styles and employees’
                    performance in federal cooperative college Kaduna FCCK. A survey research design was used
                    and primary data were gathered through the use of questionnaire. A total of 117 returned
                    questionnaires were analyzed. The study adopts structural equation model to analyze data
                    through SmartPLS 2. Findings from the study show that transactional leadership style has a
                    positive significant relationship with employees’ performance. Contrary, transformational
                    leadership style is not significantly related to employees’ performance in FCCK. The moderating
                    result shows that emotional intelligence significantly moderates the relationship between both
                    the transactional, transformational leadership styles and employees’ performance. This study
                    therefore recommends that leaders/management of FCCK should adopt the transactional
                    leadership style of exchanging rewards for high performance and reprimanding employees for
                    mistakes and low performance.</article>
            </details>
